<subSubSection id="F5E44EDE3F762711D6865A23CFAC5E1B" pageId="2" pageNumber="83" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="BD411D553F762711D6865A23CFAC5E1B" blockId="2.[151,1436,1660,1891]" pageId="2" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis id="8F8AC1473F762711D6865A23CA145E38" bold="true" box="[199,327,1833,1856]" pageId="2" pageNumber="83">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species name is an adjective derived from a composite of the Greek words “melano” (black) and “sticto” (spotted), indicating that the costal margin of forewing (
<figureCitation id="25C501D03F762711D5305A46C8E25E1B" box="[881,945,1868,1891]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="1.[151,258,997,1019]" captionTargetBox="[191,1386,202,963]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[188,1398,194,974]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Brevivalvala melanosticta sp. nov. 1. ♂, dorsal view; 2. ♂, lateral view; 3. ♂, face; 4. ♂, head in anterior view; 5. Forewing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259705/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="83">
Fig. 
<number id="0B360F723F762711D5E25A46C8E25E1B" box="[931,945,1868,1891]" pageId="2" pageNumber="83" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
) with a black spot at distal 
<number id="0B360F723F762711D2975A46CFB25E1B" box="[1238,1249,1868,1891]" pageId="2" pageNumber="83" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number id="0B360F723F762711D2AD5A46CFA85E1B" box="[1260,1275,1868,1891]" pageId="2" pageNumber="83" value="3.0">3</number>
.
</paragraph>
